node.text:
Sushi master Endo Kazutoshi looks at nine sushi scenes from popular TV shows and movies and rates them based on realism. 

He looks at "John Wick: Chapter 3 – Parabellum" (2019), "The Sopranos" S6 E1 (2006), "Gintama" episode 120 (2008), "Billions" S2E2 (2017), "East Side Sushi" (2014), "Isle of Dogs" (2018), "Samurai Gourmet" S1E7 (2017), "Dead Sushi" (2012), and "Madagascar" (2005). 
Endo is a third-generation sushi master specializing in the Edomae style of sushi, a technique particular to Tokyo. He was born in Yokohama and has been working in kitchens for 26 years. He opened Endo at the Rotunda, an omakase restaurant in the former BBC TV studios in White City, London, in 2018. The restaurant is famed for its 200-year-old hinoki wood counter and rice water imported from Endo's home town to maintain the perfect pH. He serves a 20-course sushi menu. In 2020, he opened the sushi restaurant Sumi in London's Notting Hill.

Find out more at https://www.endoatrotunda.com/

#Sushi #SushiMaking #JapaneseFood #MadagascarMovie #JohnWick3 #EndoKazutoshi

node.text:
Topped with dark chocolate icing on one half and vanilla icing on the other half, the black and white cookie is a delicious treat that can be found at grocery stores and delis all over the city.

But the cookies can vary quite a bit across regions. In the city, the cookie is known to be made flat on a denser cake with fondant icing. Meanwhile in upstate New York and Boston, the cookie is more dome-shaped and is made with a fluffier cake that’s topped with a buttercream frosting. 

We visit Zaro’s Bakery (@zarosfamilybakery), a company that ships its cookies nationwide, to get a behind-the-scenes look at the making process of the NYC style of the famous East Coast cookie.

Featuring @medhapedia

node.title: How Black and White Cookies Are Made In NYC

node.text:
Pastrami on rye has been a New York staple since the 1900s. They can be bought at old-school Jewish delis like @therealpastramiqueen. The cured meat was brought back in the late 19th and early 20th centuries when a wave of Eastern European immigrants came to the East Coast. Although delis like Pastrami Queen are nowadays a rarity, pastrami on rye is still a huge part of New York’s soul. The pastrami meat is essentially pickled, which was originally meant to preserve the meat. Pastrami can be cured or brined for 5 days to a whole week and is meant to be juicy and tender. Insider's @medhapedia  takes a closer look at how pastrami is nowadays prepped for NYC delis.

Depending on where you are in the world, you'll find a different version of bacon. In England, your bacon will be a leaner but still juicy cut from the back of the pig and cured to perfection.

Cold drinks made up 74% of Starbucks' total beverage sales in the third quarter, up from 64% two years ago, CEO Kevin Johnson said on the company's third quarter earnings call.

Starbucks baristas told Insider that they're being flooded with orders for cold drinks, saying that they often take longer to make than hot drinks.

Johnson credited the rise to strong demand for Cold Brew, Nitro Cold Brew, Iced Shaken Espresso, and Refreshers and added that cold drinks are "particularly attractive to millennial and Gen Z customers."

node.text:
Potato milk might be the next best sustainable milk option. It's also free of gluten, nuts, and animal products. Dug, the company that makes potato milk, only ships products to the UK. But you can DIY it at home.

It's white and milky and can be used as a dairy replacement in any drink, according to The Guardian. Click the link in our bio to see how to make it.

node.text:
Celebrity chefs like Sunny Anderson, Duff Goldman, Bobby Flay, and Trisha Yearwood all have their own takes on a classic chocolate milkshake. 

I tested all four of their recipes to find the best one. Anderson's chocolate-chai milkshake was my favorite. Goldman's chocolate malt was a close second.

Click the link in the bio to read the full review and get the milkshake recipes.

Story by Paige Bennett.

(Credit: Paige Bennett for Insider/Getty images)

node.accessibility_caption: A graphic with a photo of two milk shakes and celebrity chefs Sunny Anderson and Duff Goldman that reads: I tried 4 celebrity chef's recipes for chocolate milkshakes, and the best was filled with spices.

A graphic with an image of a chocolate chai milkshake and the ingredients. It reads: Sunny Anderson makes a chocolate chai milkshake that uses warm spices I already had in my pantry, plus milk, chocolate syrup, and vanilla ice cream.
I could not stop sipping this shake. It wasn't overly chocolaty or rich. The texture was perfect, too.

A graphic with an image of a malted milkshake and the ingredients. It reads: Duff Goldman tops his chocolate malted milkshake with cookies. Although it's technically a malt, this tastes exactly like what I'd want from a milkshake. It was rich and chocolaty with a thick texture that made it difficult to suck up through a straw.

A graphic with an image of a chocolate marshmallow milkshake and the ingredients. It reads: Bobby Flay layers marshmallow cream throughout his double-chocolate milkshake.
This rich and decadent milkshake is the best for chocolate lovers. It was very indulgent, though, so I could only drink a little bit.

A graphic with an image of a mint chocolate  milkshake and the ingredients. It reads:  Trisha Yearwood mixes things up with peppermint in her milkshake. While the recipe was easy to make, the final flavor was overwhelmingly minty from the peppermint extract and cookies — so much so that I didn't get much chocolate flavor.

A graphic with an image of the author, Paige Bennet holding a  chocolate chai milkshake. It reads: The chocolate chai milkshake was my favorite, but GOldman’s malt is a close second. Anderson’s recipe takes extra work, but it pays off. The spices complement hte chocolate so well and it didn't need any special toppings.
Photo showing the loaves and the ice cream pints with headline, "I tried baking Ben & Jerry's 2-ingredient ice-cream bread, and a beloved flavor made the the worst loaf"

node.text:
I tried Ben & Jerry's two-ingredient ice-cream bread using four different flavors. I enjoyed the vanilla and Chunky Monkey breads and think they'd work great for French toast. The Half Baked and Netflix & Chill'd loaves were not as good as the ice cream on its own.

Click the link in our bio to read more about the recipes.

(Credit: Paige Bennett)
#Ben&Jerrys #IceCream #baking

node.accessibility_caption: Photo showing the loaves and the ice cream pints with headline, "I tried baking Ben & Jerry's 2-ingredient ice-cream bread, and a beloved flavor made the the worst loaf"

Photo showing flour and ice cream pints with text, "Ben & Jerry's has a recipe for swirled ice-cream bread made with just the company's famous pints and self-rising flour. I was excited to make this sweet loaf with some of my favorite Ben & Jerry's flavors, as well as a basic vanilla from Häagen-Dazs."

Photo showing the vanilla ice cream loaf and pint with text, "The vanilla ice-cream bread was nice and sweet, with crisp edges and a soft and spongy middle. It was OK on its own, but this bread would be best topped with fresh berries and whipped cream. It also might make a good base for French toast."

Photo showing the Half Baked pint and loaf with text, "The Half Baked loaf was probably my least favorite even though I love the ice cream. The chocolate ice cream resulted in a weird overall flavor, and the cookie-dough bites and brownie bits led to a strange, chunky texture throughout the middle of the bread."

Photo showing the Chunky Monkey pint and loaf with text, "The Chunky Monkey loaf didn't taste like banana bread as I expected. It was probably my favorite loaf of the bunch. I loved the crunch from the walnuts, and the thick pieces of chocolate throughout wonderfully paired with the fruit's flavor."

Photo showing Netflix & Chill'd pint and loaf with text, "The Netflix & Chill'd flavor made for a difficult batter and a strange-tasting bread. Pretzel swirls might be great in ice cream, but they didn't taste the same in bread."
Photo collage showing vegetables and Michael Phelps with headline, "I tried eating, sleeping, and exercising the way Michael Phelps does in retirement, and it was surprisingly easy"

node.text:
Michael Phelps, who is now retired, shared his health regimen with GQ, and I decided to try it out. It was difficult to eat a salad every day, but I loved getting more sleep and eating more veggies. Overall, Phelps' routine helped me feel more energized and gave me a positive attitude.

Click the link in our bio to read more about Michael Phelps' routine.

(Credit: Insider)
#MichaelPhelps #DietPlans #Olympics2021

node.accessibility_caption: Photo collage showing vegetables and Michael Phelps with headline, "I tried eating, sleeping, and exercising the way Michael Phelps does in retirement, and it was surprisingly easy"

Photo collage showing spinach and smoothie with text, "I started every day with a smoothie or eggs, just like Phelps does. I had to set aside a chunk of time each morning to make the smoothie and eggs, but I realized I stayed fuller longer during the day thanks to the large, healthful breakfast."
Photo showing a salad with text, "Phelps said he and his family incorporates one salad into their diet every day. When I read that, I immediately got nervous because I've never been a fan of salads."

Photo showing vegetables with text, "I attempted to add more vegetables to my diet. All week long, I found recipes that turned these vegetables into delicious sides. With a well-balanced plate, I found myself eating less and feeling more full after dinner."

Photo showing a phone screen with alarms set with text, "Phelps also recommends getting 7 to 9 hours of sleep. I tried to do the same. I started noticing a positive change in my mood every morning when my alarm woke me up."

Photo showing the writer taking a break during a workout with text, "I tried to match Phelps' fitness routine, which involves HIIT training and cardio. As someone who rarely works out, HIIT training took a lot out of me."

Photo showing the writer drinking a smoothie with text, "I felt a positive change in my overall well-being at the end of the week. Phelps' routine is simple, and its effects completely changed my outlook on diet culture."
A graphic that shows an image of pasta and reads: Everything you need to know to make homemade pasta

node.text:
All you need to make homemade pasta are flour, eggs, and water. Fresh pasta dough can be cut into a variety of shapes, from lasagna sheets to pappardelle to ravioli. Rely on how the dough feels rather than strict measurements — you can always adjust as needed.

Click the link in our bio for more tips on making pasta from Amber Gibson.

(Credit: Getty Images/Shutterstock)

node.accessibility_caption: A graphic that shows an image of pasta and reads: Everything you need to know to make homemade pasta

A graphic that shows an image of pasta and reads: Making pasta from scratch is time-consuming but not as hard as you might think it is. It's a fun family activity with kids, or it can be relaxgin and meditative on your own

A graphic that shows an image of someone making pasta. It reads: The ingredients in homemade pasta are very simple — flour, egg, salt, oil, and flavorings/coloings — but each on contributes significantly to the final dish. For the best homemade pasts, use high quality-ingredients.
A graphic that reads: Additional materials: Medium bowl, wooden cutting board, fork, bench scraper, plastic wrap, semolina, (for dusting) pasta roller (optional), and rolling pin (optional).

A graphic that shows somone kneading dought that reads: generally aim for slightly less than one cup of flour per egg and adjust the final consistency with water or more flour. Plan on using one egg per person. Knead dough until it's smooth and uniform.

A graphich that shows somone rolling out pasta using a pasta roller. It reads: A tabletop pasta sheeter can roll out and cut your noodles quickly. To roll out dought at home, you can always use a rolling pun, but you may have trouble getting it thin enough. Pasta should be cooked for 30 seconds to 2 minutes according to chef adam berger.

A graphic that reads: Tips for the best homemade pasta: let yourself make a mess. You'll probably end up with flour all over your kitch. Accoepting it can ensure you have more fun enjoying the process. Practice makes perfect. Berger says a regular Pasta-making routine (several timese a month) is necessary to get the hang of it.
Photo of a chicken sandwich in an In-N-Out wrapper with the headline, "TikTokers are claiming that In-N-Out sells chicken sandwiches, but the chain says the 'secret' menu item doesn't exist."

node.text:
Videos of chicken sandwiches at In-N-Out are going viral on TikTok, with users claiming that they’re hidden on the beloved chain’s “secret” menu.

But a spokesperson for the chain told Insider that the videos are fake to “attract attention,” and that there are no plans for the chain to wade into the ongoing fried-chicken sandwich wars between other fast-food giants.

Read the full story by clicking the link in our bio.

(Credit: andynot2021/TikTok)

node.text:
Sushi master Endo Kazutoshi looks at nine sushi scenes from popular TV shows and movies and rates them based on realism. 

He looks at "John Wick: Chapter 3 – Parabellum" (2019), "The Sopranos" S6 E1 (2006), "Gintama" episode 120 (2008), "Billions" S2E2 (2017), "East Side Sushi" (2014), "Isle of Dogs" (2018), "Samurai Gourmet" S1E7 (2017), "Dead Sushi" (2012), and "Madagascar" (2005). 
Endo is a third-generation sushi master specializing in the Edomae style of sushi, a technique particular to Tokyo. He was born in Yokohama and has been working in kitchens for 26 years. He opened Endo at the Rotunda, an omakase restaurant in the former BBC TV studios in White City, London, in 2018. The restaurant is famed for its 200-year-old hinoki wood counter and rice water imported from Endo's home town to maintain the perfect pH. He serves a 20-course sushi menu. In 2020, he opened the sushi restaurant Sumi in London's Notting Hill.

Find out more at https://www.endoatrotunda.com/

I tried recipes from "Martha Stewart's Slow Cooker," written by the editors of Martha Stewart Living. The recipes were easy to make and most only required a few ingredients. The chef's slow cooker macaroni and cheese was the most flavorful macaroni and cheese I've ever had.

Click the link in our bio to read the full story.

(Credit: Insider)

Photo showing the chicken curry with text, "I made multiple chicken dishes from the cookbook but liked the chef's chicken curry the least. The finished dish was edible, but I thought it was severely lacking in flavor."

Photo showing the poached salmon with salsa verde with text, "The recipe for poached salmon with salsa verde was extremely easy to make, but it didn't blow me away. While the salmon tasted very simple on its own, the salsa verde packed a ton of flavor."

Photo showing the pulled pork sandwich with text, "The pulled pork recipe was middle-of-the-road. I made my own homemade coleslaw and served it on a white potato roll. The finished product was delicious, but I was craving a little barbecue sauce to make it even better."

Photo showing the macaroni and cheese with text, "I also made Martha Stewart's three-cheese macaroni and cheese. This was by far the most flavorful macaroni and cheese I've ever had, and I thought it was very easy to make in the slow cooker."

Photo showing the chicken thighs with cilantro chutney with text, "The recipe for chicken thighs with cilantro chutney was the most flavorful and impressive dish I made. I paired the chicken thighs with rice and a dollop of yogurt, per the recipe's instructions. It tasted fresh, light, and delicious."
